      <summary class="h3">DRUG H/O : </summary>
      <iframe src="DRUG_HISTORY.html" frameborder="0"></iframe> </details>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>IV. PAST MEDICAL HISTORY</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Previous orthopedic problems: (Fractures, dislocations, sprains,
          surgeries - dates, type, outcome, complications)</li>
        <li>Chronic illnesses: (e.g., Osteoarthritis, Rheumatoid Arthritis,
          Gout, Psoriatic Arthritis, Ankylosing Spondylitis, Osteoporosis,
          Diabetes Mellitus, Peripheral Vascular Disease, Connective Tissue
          Diseases, Cancer - especially bone mets, Thyroid disease)</li>
        <li>Childhood illnesses: (e.g., DDH, Perthes, SUFE, rickets, scoliosis)</li>
        <li>Previous surgeries (non-orthopedic, note any impact on mobility or
          anaesthesia risk).</li>
        <li>Previous hospitalizations (reason, duration, outcome).</li>
        <li>Current Medications: (Prescribed, over-the-counter, supplements -
          name, dose, frequency, duration, reason for taking. Specifically ask
          about NSAIDs, steroids, anticoagulants, bisphosphonates, DMARDs)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>Drug HISTORY</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>NSAIDs</li>
        <li>steroids</li>
        <li>anticoagulants</li>
        <li>DMARDs</li>
        <details>
          <summary>HERBAL REMEDIES INTERACTIONS</summary>
          <iframe src="HERBAL_REMEDIES_INTERACTIONS.html"></iframe> </details>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>ALLERGY HISTORY</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Drug allergies</li>
        <li>Food allergies</li>
        <li>Environmental allergies</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <details>
        <summary class="h3"><a href="Family_history.html">FAMILY H/O:</a></summary>
        <iframe src="Family_history.html" frameborder="0"></iframe> </details>
    </div>
    <details>
      <summary class="h3">PERSONAL H/O</summary>
      <iframe src="Personal_history.html"></iframe> </details>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>VI. PERSONAL AND SOCIAL HISTORY</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Occupation:</strong> (Current and past, nature of work -
          sedentary, manual labor, repetitive tasks, risk of injury)</li>
        <li><strong>Living Situation:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Type of dwelling: (House, apartment - stairs, accessibility)</li>
            <li>Lives with whom? (Support system)</li>
            <li>Any modifications needed at home?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Activities of Daily Living (ADLs):</strong> (Independent,
          needs assistance - specify which tasks)</li>
        <li><strong>Mobility:</strong> (Walks unaided, uses
          stick/crutch/frame/wheelchair. Gait abnormalities.)</li>
        <li><strong>Diet:</strong> (Adequacy, calcium/vitamin D intake, weight -
          BMI)</li>
        <li><strong>Exercise/Physical Activity:</strong> (Type, frequency,
          duration. Sports participation.)</li>
        <ol>
          <li> injury and treatment impact on that activity.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Smoking:</strong> (Yes/No. If yes, pack-years. If ex-smoker,
          when quit?) - bone healing and surgical risk.</li>
        <li><strong>Alcohol:</strong> (Yes/No. If yes, type and quantity per
          week) - Risk for osteoporosis, AVN, falls.</li>
        <li><strong>Travel History:</strong> (Recent, relevant for infections
          e.g., Lyme disease, TB)</li>
        <li><strong>Impact of condition on mental health:</strong> (Anxiety,
          depression)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">SEXUAL HISTORY</summary>
        <iframe src="Sexual_History_section_CASE_SHEET.html" frameborder="0"></iframe>
      </details>
      <p>Hepatitis</p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p> </p>
      <p> </p>
    </div>
    <details>
      <summary class="h3">MENSTRUAL HISTORY</summary>
      <iframe src="MENSTRUAL_HISTORY_case_sheet_part.html" frameborder="0"></iframe>
    </details>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>VII. REVIEW OF SYSTEMS (Briefly, focusing on red flags or related
        symptoms)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>General:</strong> Unexplained weight loss, fever, chills,
          night sweats, fatigue, appetite changes.</li>
        <li><strong>Cardiovascular:</strong> Chest pain, palpitations, shortness
          of breath on exertion, orthopnea, PND, edema. (Fitness for surgery)</li>
        <li><strong>Respiratory:</strong> Cough, sputum, hemoptysis, wheezing,
          shortness of breath. (Fitness for surgery)</li>
        <li><strong>Gastrointestinal:</strong> Nausea, vomiting, diarrhea,
          constipation, abdominal pain, melena, hematemesis. (NSAID side
          effects, referred pain)</li>
        <li><strong>Genitourinary:</strong> Dysuria, frequency, urgency,
          hematuria, incontinence, erectile dysfunction. (Cauda equina, prostate
          issues referring pain)</li>
        <li><strong>Neurological:</strong> Headache, dizziness, faints,
          seizures, weakness, numbness, tingling, changes in sensation,
          coordination, bladder or bowel dysfunction.</li>
        <li><strong>Endocrine:</strong> Heat/cold intolerance, polyuria,
          polydipsia. (Diabetes, thyroid)</li>
        <li><strong>Dermatological:</strong> Rashes, lesions, nail changes, skin
          ulcers. (Psoriatic arthritis, vasculitis, PVD)</li>
        <li><strong>Hematological:</strong> Easy bruising, bleeding tendencies.
          (Clotting disorders, medication side effects)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <br>
    <h2>SUMMARIZATION OF HISTORY</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>summarize what is heard so far</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>VIII. GENERAL PHYSICAL EXAMINATION</h3>
      <h4>Chaperone</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Appearance:</strong> Alert, comfortable/in distress,
          well/unwell, nutritional status.</li>
        <li><strong>Vital Signs:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Temperature: [...&Acirc;&deg;C]</li>
            <li>Pulse: [...bpm, rhythm, volume, character]</li>
            <li>Blood Pressure: [.../... mmHg, arm, cuff size]</li>
            <li>Respiratory Rate: [...breaths/min, pattern]</li>
            <li>SpO2: [...% on room air/oxygen]</li>
            <li>Weight: [...kg], Height: [...cm], BMI: [...kg/m&Acirc;&sup2;]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Gait:</strong> (Observe if possible: normal, antalgic,
          Trendelenburg, waddling, steppage, ataxic, parkinsonian, use of aids)</li>
        <li><strong>Posture:</strong> (e.g., kyphosis, scoliosis, lordosis,
          pelvic tilt)</li>
        <li><strong>Overall musculoskeletal build and symmetry.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Skin:</strong> Pallor, jaundice, cyanosis, rashes, scars,
          bruising.</li>
        <li><strong>Lymph Nodes:</strong> Palpable? (Site, size, consistency,
          tenderness, mobility) - especially regional to affected area.</li>
        <li><strong>Hands:</strong> Nail changes (psoriasis, clubbing),
          Heberden's/Bouchard's nodes, ulnar deviation, Swan neck/Boutonniere
          deformities, palmar erythema, muscle wasting.</li>
        <li><strong>Eyes:</strong> Conjunctival pallor, scleral icterus, signs
          of uveitis/iritis (associated with spondyloarthropathies).</li>
        <li><strong>Mouth:</strong> Oral ulcers, dental hygiene.</li>
        <li>(Brief exam of other systems as indicated by ROS)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>IX. LOCAL / REGIONAL MUSCULOSKELETAL EXAMINATION</h3>
      <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
      <p class="ortho-specific">(Follow "Look, Feel, Move, Special Tests,
        Neurovascular" for the affected area and related joints. Compare with
        the contralateral side.)</p>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3"><b>EXPAND EXAMINATION</b>: <b><u>All </u><u>Joints</u></b>
        </summary>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> [e.g., Right Knee, Lumbar Spine,
          Both Shoulders]</p>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Gait:</strong> (Re-assess specific to the complaint if not
            fully done in GPE)</li>
          <li><strong>Posture/Alignment:</strong> (</li>
          <ul>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Deformites</b></li>
              <li>varus, </li>
              <li>valgus, </li>
              <li>flexion, </li>
              <li>extension, </li>
              <li>rotational; </li>
              <li>scoliosis, </li>
              <li>kyphosis, </li>
              <li>loss of lordosis)</li>
            </ul>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Swelling:</strong> (</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Location, </li>
            <li>size, </li>
            <li>shape, </li>
            <li>diffuse/localized)</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Skin Changes:</strong> (</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Color - redness, bruising, discoloration; </li>
            <li>scars, </li>
            <li>sinuses, </li>
            <li>ulcers, </li>
            <li>rashes, </li>
            <li>venous prominence)</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Muscle Wasting/Bulk:</strong> (Compare sides, e.g.,
            quadriceps, glutei, deltoids)</li>
          <li><strong>Bony Landmarks:</strong> (Prominence, asymmetry)</li>
          <li><strong>Ability to perform functional tasks:</strong> (e.g.,
            squat, single leg stance, touch toes)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> (Warmth over joint/area - compare
            sides)</li>
          <li><strong>Tenderness:</strong> (Localize precisely - bony landmarks,
            joint line, soft tissues, ligaments, tendons, muscles. Note
            patient's reaction.)</li>
          <li><strong>Swelling:</strong> (Confirm presence, consistency - soft,
            firm, fluctuant, bony; size, tenderness, local rise in temperature)
            <ul>
              <li>Effusion tests (e.g., bulge sign, patellar tap for knee)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Crepitus:</strong> (Palpable grinding with movement)</li>
          <li><strong>Bony Landmarks:</strong> (Assess for irregularity,
            tenderness)</li>
          <li><strong>Muscle Tone/Bulk:</strong> (Confirm wasting)</li>
          <li><strong>Pulses:</strong> (Distal to injury/affected area, e.g.,
            dorsalis pedis, posterior tibial for lower limb; radial, ulnar for
            upper limb)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Active Range of Motion (AROM):</strong> (Patient moves the
            joint themselves. Note range, pain, willingness to move, crepitus.)
            <ul>
              <li>[Specify joint and movements, e.g., Knee Flexion:
                0-135&Acirc;&deg;, Extension: 0&Acirc;&deg;]</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Passive Range of Motion (PROM):</strong> (Examiner moves
            the joint. Note range, pain, end-feel, crepitus, blocks to
            movement.)
            <ul>
              <li>[Specify joint and movements]</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Abnormal Movements:</strong> (e.g., hypermobility,
            instability)</li>
          <li><strong>Pain on Movement:</strong> (Note which movements are
            painful)</li>
          <li><strong>Strength (MRC Scale 0-5):</strong> (Test specific muscle
            groups against resistance. Compare sides.)
            <ul>
              <li>0: No contraction</li>
              <li>1: Flicker or trace of contraction</li>
              <li>2: Active movement, with gravity eliminated</li>
              <li>3: Active movement against gravity</li>
              <li>4: Active movement against gravity and resistance</li>
              <li>5: Normal power</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: SHOULDER </summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ERskTOC5LR4" title="SHOULDER EXAMINATION OSCE VIDEO - "
            height="864" frameborder="0" width="1520"></iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure:
            "Now I'm going to do a shoulder examination. This includes first of
            all we'll have the look of the joint, we'll feel the joint and then
            we'll do some movements" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=50s">Video
              0:50-0:57</a>). Ensure adequate exposure: "for the purpose of
            examination I want you to undress above your waist" (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=57s">Video
              0:57-1:00</a>). Offer/confirm chaperone: "I have a chaperone to
            ensure your privacy" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=60s">Video
              1:00-1:02</a>). Obtain consent: "May I proceed?" (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=62s">Video
              1:02</a>). Compare with the contralateral side throughout.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Both Shoulders (starting with
          asymptomatic side if one is affected)</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=68s">Video
            1:08</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>POSITIONS</strong></li>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>From the Front, <br>
              </strong></li>
            <li><strong>Side, and <br>
              </strong></li>
            <li><strong>Back:</strong><br>
              <strong></strong></li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Patient Standing in Anatomical Position:</strong> (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=68s">Video
              1:08-1:11</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Alignment:</strong> Check alignment of shoulder
                joints, anterior superior iliac spine, knee, and ankle joint
                &ndash; all should be in the same plane. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=73s">Video
                  1:13-1:20</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=92s">Video
                  1:32-1:40</a>)</li>
              <li>Shoulder joint is aligned. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=101s">Video
                  1:41-1:44</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>From the Front, Side, and Back:</strong> (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=84s">Video
              1:24-1:28</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=109s">Video
              1:49-1:54</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Swelling:</strong> (</li>
              <ul>
                <li>site</li>
                <li>size, </li>
                <li>shape, </li>
                <li>diffuse/localized).</li>
              </ul>
              <li><strong>Skin Changes:</strong> (Color - redness, bruising,
                discoloration; scars, sinuses, ulcers, rashes, venous
                prominence).</li>
              <li><strong>Muscle Wasting/Bulk:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Deltoid wasting: "no deltoid wasting". (<a class="timestamp"
                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=104s">Video
                      1:44-1:46</a>)</li>
                  <li>Trapezius muscle wasting (from back). (<a class="timestamp"
                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=120s">Video
                      2:00-2:07</a>)</li>
                  <li>Compare sides.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Deformity:</strong> (e.g., squaring of shoulder,
                clavicular prominence, Sprengel's shoulder).</li>
              <li><strong>Bony Landmarks:</strong> (Prominence, asymmetry of
                clavicle, AC joint, scapula).</li>
              <li><strong>Scapula:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Winging of scapula (from back). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=120s">Video
                      2:00-2:02</a>)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=130s">Video
            2:10</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(Keep looking at patient's face for any tenderness (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=151s">Video
              2:31</a>). Compare both sides (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=136s">Video
              2:16</a>).)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> Over the joint/area, compare both
            sides. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=134s">Video
              2:14-2:16</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Tenderness over</strong></li>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>&nbsp;Bony Landmarks and <br>
              </strong></li>
            <li><strong>Soft Tissues (one by one on each side <a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=146s">Video
                  2:26</a>):</strong>
              <ul>
              </ul>
              Sternoclavicular (SC) joint. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=141s">Video
                2:21-2:26</a>)<br>
              Clavicle along its length. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=154s">Video
                2:34</a>)<br>
              Acromioclavicular (AC) joint. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=162s">Video
                2:42</a>)<br>
              Head of Humerus / End of Humerus. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=166s">Video
                2:46</a>)<br>
              Greater Tuberosity. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=173s">Video
                2:53</a>)<br>
              Bicipital groove.<br>
              Rotator cuff tendons.<br>
              Deltoid muscle.
              <ul>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Palpation from the Back (Patient turns around <a class="timestamp"
                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=177s">Video
                2:57-2:59</a>):</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Scapula:&nbsp; (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=181s">Video
                  3:01-3:07</a>)</li>
              <ul>
                <li>Borders and</li>
                <li>wing of scapula.</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Repeat on both sides. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=191s">Video
                  3:11</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Swelling:</strong> (Confirm presence, consistency - soft,
            firm, fluctuant; size, tenderness).</li>
          <li><strong>Crepitus:</strong> (Palpable grinding with movement).</li>
          <li><strong>Muscle Tone/Bulk:</strong> (Confirm wasting).</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=199s">Video
            3:19</a> for start of movements)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Active Range of Motion (AROM):</strong> (Patient performs.
            Note range, pain, crepitus, willingness.)
            <ul>
              <li>Flexion: "take it as long as you can go" (forward). (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=200s">Video
                  3:20-3:25</a>)</li>
              <li>Extension: "and then we come down... extension... maximum
                where the patient can go". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=205s">Video
                  3:25-3:32</a>)</li>
              <li>Abduction: "on the side... go as long as you can go". (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=214s">Video
                  3:34-3:43</a>)</li>
              <li>Adduction: "cross your arms". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=224s">Video
                  3:44-3:50</a>)</li>
              <li>External Rotation: (Elbows at side, flexed to 90&deg;, rotate
                outwards). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=234s">Video
                  3:54-3:59</a>)</li>
              <li>Internal Rotation: (Reach behind back, note vertebral level
                reached by thumb). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=234s">Video
                  3:54-4:04</a>, specific action for internal rotation not fully
                detailed but implied with "external and internal rotation").</li>
              <li>Demonstration of restricted movements in frozen shoulder (Left
                Arm): Abduction (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=256s">Video
                  4:16-4:22</a>), Flexion (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=268s">Video
                  4:28-4:37</a>), External Rotation (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=279s">Video
                  4:39-4:50</a>).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Passive Range of Motion (PROM):</strong> (Examiner moves
            the joint. Note range, pain, end-feel, crepitus. Video mentions
            passive movement restriction is same as active for frozen shoulder (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERskTOC5LR4&amp;t=292s">Video
              4:52-4:57</a>) but doesn't explicitly demonstrate PROM sequence
            for all movements).</li>
          <li><strong>Abnormal Movements:</strong> (e.g., hypermobility,
            instability).</li>
          <li><strong>Pain on Movement:</strong> (Note which movements are
            painful).</li>
          <li><strong>Strength (MRC Scale 0-5):</strong> (Test specific muscle
            groups against resistance. Compare sides.)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>D. SPECIAL TESTS</h4>
        <p class="ortho-specific">(Perform relevant tests based on suspected
          pathology. Document positive/negative findings.)</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Shoulder:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Rotator Cuff: Jobe's (<a href="https://youtu.be/ERskTOC5LR4?t=319">empty
                  can</a>), Lift-off, Hawkins-Kennedy, Neer's, (<a href="https://youtu.be/ERskTOC5LR4?t=319">Painful
                  arc</a>)</li>
              <li>Instability: Apprehension test, Sulcus sign</li>
              <li>Biceps: Speed's test, Yergason's test</li>
              <li>AC Joint: Scarf test (cross-body adduction)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: SPINE</summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/EXAMPLE_SPINE_VIDEO" title="SPINE EXAMINATION OSCE VIDEO"
            height="864" frameborder="0" width="1520"></iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure.
            Ensure adequate exposure. Offer/confirm chaperone. Obtain consent.
            Compare with the contralateral side.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Spine (Cervical, Thoracic, Lumbar,
          Sacral)</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>POSITIONS</strong>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>From the Front, Side, and Back</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Patient Standing in Anatomical Position:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Alignment:</strong> Check spinal curves (cervical
                lordosis, thoracic kyphosis, lumbar lordosis)</li>
              <li><strong>Posture:</strong> Note any scoliosis, kyphosis, or
                other postural abnormalities</li>
              <li><strong>Muscle Bulk:</strong> Look for paraspinal muscle
                wasting or asymmetry</li>
              <li><strong>Skin Changes:</strong> Look for tufts of hair,
                dimples, or skin lesions over the spine</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL)</h4>
        <p><em>(Keep looking at patient's face for any tenderness. Compare both
            sides.)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Spinous Processes:</strong> Palpate each vertebra for
            tenderness or step-off</li>
          <li><strong>Paraspinal Muscles:</strong> Check for spasm or tenderness</li>
          <li><strong>Sacroiliac Joints:</strong> Check for tenderness</li>
          <li><strong>Spinal Tenderness:</strong> Note any localized or
            radiating tenderness</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Active Range of Motion:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Flexion/Extension</li>
              <li>Lateral Flexion (Left/Right)</li>
              <li>Rotation (Left/Right)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Special Tests:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Spurling's test (cervical radiculopathy)</li>
              <li>Lhermitte's sign</li>
              <li>Lasegue's test (straight leg raise)</li>
              <li>Femoral stretch test</li>
              <li>Schober's test (lumbar mobility)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: ELBOW</summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/xejdb-T98nY" title="Elbow Examination - OSCE Guide | Aspire PLAB2/UKMLA Academy"
            height="835" frameborder="0" width="1468"></iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure:
            "any joint examination... look feel move" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=8s">Video
              0:08-0:16</a>). Ensure adequate exposure. Offer/confirm chaperone.
            Obtain consent. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=24s">Video
              0:24-0:35</a> for general principles). Compare with the
            contralateral side.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Both Elbows</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=29s">Video
            0:29</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Patient position:</strong> Anatomical position</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Ask patient to join legs and have palms facing towards examiner.
              (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=54s">Video
                0:54-1:00</a>)</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>From the Front:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=60s">Video
              1:00-1:09</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Scars</li>
              <li>Swelling</li>
              <li>Erythema (Irritma mentioned in video)</li>
              <li>Carrying angle (Normal: 5-15 degrees) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=64s">Video
                  1:04-1:09</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>From the Side and Back:</strong> Inform patient before
            moving. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=73s">Video
              1:13-1:23</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Scars (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=86s">Video
                  1:26</a>)</li>
              <li>Swelling (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=86s">Video
                  1:26</a>)</li>
              <li>Erythema (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=86s">Video
                  1:26</a>)</li>
              <li>Psoriatic plaques (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=91s">Video
                  1:31</a>)</li>
              <li>Rheumatoid nodules (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=91s">Video
                  1:31-1:33</a>)</li>
              <li>Muscle wasting</li>
              <li>Sinuses</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=97s">Video
            1:37</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(Inform patient: "Now I'm going to touch your elbow" (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=97s">Video
              1:37</a>). Keep looking at patient's face for tenderness.)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> "no local rise of temperature". (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=101s">Video
              1:41-1:44</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Bony Landmarks &amp; Tendons for Tenderness:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Medial epicondyle. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=104s">Video
                  1:44-1:49</a>)</li>
              <li>Lateral epicondyle. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=112s">Video
                  1:52-1:55</a>)</li>
              <li>Olecranon process. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=115s">Video
                  1:55-1:59</a>)</li>
              <li>Biceps tendon (ask patient to bend elbow). (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=120s">Video
                  2:00-2:06</a>)</li>
              <li>Radial head.</li>
              <li>Common extensor and flexor origins.</li>
              <li>Ulnar nerve in the cubital tunnel.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=129s">Video
            2:09</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(Active movements demonstrated)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Flexion: "bend your arms for me". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=133s">Video
              2:13-2:15</a>)</li>
          <li>Extension: "now all the way back down". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=135s">Video
              2:15-2:20</a>)</li>
          <li>Supination: "palm facing upward". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=140s">Video
              2:20</a>)</li>
          <li>Pronation: "then turn them over". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=140s">Video
              2:20-2:23</a>)</li>
          <li>(Return to supination: "Now turn them back again" <a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=145s">Video
              2:25</a>)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>D. SPECIAL TESTS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=152s">Video
            2:32</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(For lateral epicondylitis - Tennis Elbow; Medial epicondylitis -
            Golfer's Elbow (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=45s">Video
              0:45-0:51</a>))</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Patient bends elbow and makes a fist. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=154s">Video
              2:34-2:36</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Resisted Wrist Extension (variation of Cozen's test):</strong>
            "press against my force". (Examiner resists wrist extension,
            checking for pain). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=159s">Video
              2:39-2:42</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Resisted Wrist Flexion (Medial epicondylitis test):</strong>
            "press down against my force". (Examiner resists wrist flexion,
            checking for pain). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=162s">Video
              2:42-2:49</a>)</li>
          <li>Mill's test (not explicitly shown but is a standard test for
            lateral epicondylitis).</li>
          <li>Tinel's test at elbow (ulnar nerve - not shown).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em><b>Completion of Examination:</b> "To
            complete elbow examination make sure you examine other elbow and you
            will examine one joint above and one joint below as well. And do not
            forget to do the full neurological examination." (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xejdb-T98nY&amp;t=172s">Video
              2:52-3:01</a>)</em></p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: WRIST AND HAND</summary>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure.
            Ensure adequate exposure. Offer/confirm chaperone. Obtain consent.
            Compare with the contralateral side.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Both Wrists and Hands</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dorsal and Palmar Aspects:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Deformities (swan neck, boutonniere, mallet finger, etc.)</li>
              <li>Swelling, muscle wasting (thenar, hypothenar, interossei)</li>
              <li>Skin changes, nail changes, scars</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Distal radioulnar joint</li>
          <li>Lister's tubercle</li>
          <li>Anatomical snuffbox</li>
          <li>Scaphoid</li>
          <li>Metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints</li>
          <li>Proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints</li>
          <li>Distal interphalangeal (DIP) joints</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Wrist: Flexion/Extension, Radial/Ulnar deviation</li>
          <li>Fingers: MCP, PIP, DIP flexion/extension</li>
          <li>Thumb: Opposition, abduction, adduction</li>
          <li>Special Tests:
            <ul>
              <li>Finkelstein's test (de Quervain's tenosynovitis)</li>
              <li>Phalen's test (carpal tunnel syndrome)</li>
              <li>Tinel's test at wrist (median nerve)</li>
              <li>Froment's sign (ulnar nerve palsy)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: HIP</summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/EXAMPLE_HIP_VIDEO" title="HIP EXAMINATION OSCE VIDEO"
            height="864" frameborder="0" width="1520"></iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure.
            Ensure adequate exposure. Offer/confirm chaperone. Obtain consent.
            Compare with the contralateral side.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Both Hips</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Standing:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Pelvic tilt, limb length discrepancy, muscle wasting</li>
              <li>Gait (antalgic, Trendelenburg, etc.)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Supine:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Deformity, swelling, scars, sinuses</li>
              <li>Limb position (flexion, abduction, external rotation)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Anterior superior iliac spine (ASIS)</li>
          <li>Greater trochanter</li>
          <li>Iliotibial band</li>
          <li>Inguinal region (femoral pulse, lymph nodes)</li>
          <li>Ischial tuberosity (in lateral position)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Flexion (with knee flexed)</li>
          <li>Extension (Thomas test)</li>
          <li>Abduction/Adduction</li>
          <li>Internal/External rotation (hip and knee flexed to 90&deg;)</li>
          <li>Special Tests:
            <ul>
              <li>Trendelenburg test</li>
              <li>Thomas test (fixed flexion deformity)</li>
              <li>FABER/Patrick's test (sacroiliac joint pathology)</li>
              <li>Trendelenburg test</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </details>
      <details open="">
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: KNEE</summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZE5SDPKc-kg" title="Knee Examination by Dr. Ankur Garg"
            frameborder="0"> </iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure:
            "I'll be examining your knee" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=26s">Video
              0:26-0:31</a>). Ensure adequate exposure: "I want you to
            undress... below your waist" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=33s">Video
              0:33-0:34</a>) - (More accurately, above knee to mid-thigh).
            Offer/confirm chaperone: "I have a chaperone to ensure privacy" (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=34s">Video
              0:34-0:36</a>). Obtain consent. Compare with the contralateral
            side. Ask about pain before starting.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Both Knees</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Positions :</strong></li>
          <ul>
            <li><br>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Standing:</strong> "stand in this way the palm facing
            towards me and join your legs" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=39s">Video
              0:39-0:43</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Alignment of Joints:</strong> Check shoulder, anterior
                superior iliac spine, knee, and ankle are in the same plane (no
                limb length discrepancy). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=48s">Video
                  0:48-0:59</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>From Front, Side, and Back:</strong> Inform patient
                before moving: "John what do you mind if I have a look at your
                legs and for that I will be going to your side and to your back
                is that all right" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=69s">Video
                  1:09-1:18</a>).
                <ul>
                  <li>Redness, swelling, sign of injury, trauma side, deformity,
                    scar mark of surgery. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=80s">Video
                      1:20-1:31</a>)</li>
                  <li>Popliteal Fossa (from back): No cysts, no fullness. (<a class="timestamp"
                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=91s">Video
                      1:31-1:35</a>)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Gait:</strong> Ask patient to take a few steps. "Gate
                of the patient is also normal". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=95s">Video
                  1:35-1:52</a>)</li>
              <li>Quadriceps wasting.</li>
              <li>Effusion.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Sitting/Supine:</strong> (Patient lies down on couch for
            palpation <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=118s">Video
              1:58-2:02</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Swelling, scars, sinuses.</li>
              <li>Patella position and alignment.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=116s">Video
            1:56</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(Inform : "brett now I'll have a feel of your knee" (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=122s">Video
              2:02</a>). Look at patient's face for tenderness (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=156s">Video
              2:36</a>).)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> Compare one knee with the other, and
            the same knee with the shin. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=125s">Video
              2:05-2:16</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Tenderness (Knees bent: "bend the knee and just relax go
              floppy" <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=140s">Video
                2:20-2:26</a>):</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Borders of Patella (Medial and Lateral). (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=150s">Video
                  2:30-2:45</a>)</li>
              <li>Joint Line (Medial and Lateral). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=165s">Video
                  2:45-2:54</a>)</li>
              <li>Popliteal Fossa (with fingers, for fullness/cyst). (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=176s">Video
                  2:56-3:01</a>)</li>
              <li>(Patient straightens leg <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=183s">Video
                  3:03</a>)</li>
              <li>Patellar Tendon. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=188s">Video
                  3:08-3:12</a>)</li>
              <li>Tibial Tuberosity. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=192s">Video
                  3:12-3:16</a>)</li>
              <li>Quadriceps tendon.</li>
              <li>Pes anserine bursa.</li>
              <li>Fibular head.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Tests for Effusion:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=201s">Video
              3:21</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Sweep / Swipe Test (Minor Effusion):</strong> </li>
              <li>&nbsp;Sweep fluid up from medial aspect, hold in suprapatellar
                pouch, then swipe down lateral aspect to see bulge on medial
                side. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=207s">Video
                  3:27-4:00</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>Patellar Tap (Major Effusion):</strong> </li>
              <li>Milk fluid down into knee from suprapatellar pouch, hold with
                one hand, tap patella with other. Floating patella suggests
                major effusion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=246s">Video
                  4:06-4:30</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Patellar Grind Test (Patellofemoral Arthritis):</strong> </li>
          <li>Hand on upper border of patella, make a grip, ask patient to tense
            thigh muscle. Pain suggests inflamed patellofemoral joint. (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=276s">Video
              4:36-4:58</a>)</li>
          <li>Crepitus (palpable grinding with movement).</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=305s">Video
            5:05</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Active Range of Motion:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Flexion: "bend your right knee and bring your heel as much as
                close to your bottom". (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=312s">Video
                  5:12-5:20</a>)</li>
              <li>Extension (return from flexion). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=320s">Video
                  5:20-5:23</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>(Passive range of motion should also be assessed if active is
            limited or painful).</li>
          <li>Patellar mobility and apprehension test.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>D. SPECIAL TESTS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=326s">Video
            5:26</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Collateral Ligament Stress Tests:</strong> (Patient relax
            <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=337s">Video
              5:37</a>, lift knee <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=342s">Video
              5:42</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong><b>Valgus </b></strong>Stress Test <strong>( <b>MCL</b>):</strong>
              </li>
              <li>Apply lateral stress (push medially with outer hand, bring
                lower leg laterally with inner hand). Checks MCL. Look for
                tenderness/laxity. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=346s">Video
                  5:46-6:11</a>, "lateral stress test" termed in video). Perform
                at 0&deg; and 30&deg; of flexion.</li>
              <li><strong><em>Varus </em></strong><em></em>Stress Test <strong>(
                  <em>LCL</em>):</strong> </li>
              <li>Apply medial stress (push laterally with inner hand, bring
                lower leg medially with outer hand). Checks LCL. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=384s">Video
                  6:24-6:44</a>, "medial stress test" termed in video). Perform
                at 0&deg; and 30&deg; of flexion.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>McMurray's Test (Meniscal Tears):</strong> Leg at 90&deg;
            flexion, hand on knee joint to feel click. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=407s">Video
              6:47-6:58</a>) </li>
          <li><img src="https://healthjade.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/Knee-meniscus-anatomy.jpg"
              alt="Meniscus tear knee symptoms, signs, diagnosis, treatment and recovery"
              style="width: 637px; height: 369px;">
            <ul>
              <li><b>Medial </b>Meniscus: </li>
              <li>Bring heel medially (external rotation of tibia), slide down
                in rotation (extend knee) while applying valgus stress. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=428s">Video
                  7:08-7:20</a>)</li>
              <li><em>Lateral </em>Meniscus: </li>
              <li>Bring heel laterally (internal rotation of tibia), slide down
                in rotation (extend knee) while applying varus stress. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=444s">Video
                  7:24-7:33</a>)</li>
              <li>Positive: Palpable/audible click and/or pain.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Drawer Tests (Cruciate Ligaments):</strong> Patient bends
            leg, examiner sits on patient's foot to stabilize. (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=465s">Video
              7:45-8:05</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><b>Anterior </b>Drawer Test (<b>ACL</b>): Pull tibia forward.
                (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=487s">Video
                  8:07-8:19</a>)</li>
              <li><em>Posterior </em>Drawer Test (<em>PCL</em>): Push tibia
                backward. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=499s">Video
                  8:19-8:24</a>)</li>
              <li>Positive: Pain or excessive movement.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Lachman test (ACL - not explicitly shown, but a key test).</li>
          <li>Thessaly test (meniscal pathology - not explicitly shown).</li>
          <li>Patellar apprehension test (already listed under movement).</li>
          <li>Patellar grind test (already listed under palpation).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em><b>Completion:</b> "to finish the
            examination always whenever be checking for any joint we have to
            examine one joint above and one joint below and we should complete
            it with the full neurological examination we can also check for the
            distal pulses" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZE5SDPKc-kg&amp;t=519s">Video
              8:39-8:51</a>).</em></p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: ANKLE AND FOOT</summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
            src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Tjz24MT56A0" title="ANKLE AND FOOT EXAMINATION OSCE VIDEO"
            height="864" frameborder="0" width="1520"></iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain procedure:
            "now I'll be examining your tummy [foot/ankle]..." (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=0s">Video
              0:00</a> - note: examiner says 'tummy' initially, likely a slip,
            context is ankle/foot). Ensure adequate exposure "below the knee" (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=27s">Video
              0:27</a>). Offer/confirm chaperone: "make sure you have The
            Chaperone to ensure the patient privacy" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=28s">Video
              0:28-0:32</a>). Obtain consent: "before you start make sure you
            take consent" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=32s">Video
              0:32-0:35</a>). Compare with the contralateral side.)</em></p>
        <p><strong>AREA(S) EXAMINED:</strong> Both Ankles and Feet</p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. INSPECTION (LOOK) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=39s">Video
            0:39</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General Inspection (Front, Side, Back):</strong> (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=42s">Video
              0:42-0:58</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Redness. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=46s">Video
                  0:46</a>)</li>
              <li>Swelling. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=46s">Video
                  0:46</a>)</li>
              <li>Scar marks from surgery. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=48s">Video
                  0:48-0:50</a>)</li>
              <li>Bruises. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=50s">Video
                  0:50-0:52</a>)</li>
              <li>Deformities (bunions, hammertoes, claw toes).</li>
              <li>Arch height (pes planus/cavus).</li>
              <li>Hindfoot alignment (varus/valgus).</li>
              <li>Forefoot alignment (adductus/abductus).</li>
              <li>Callosities, corns.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Patient Standing:</strong> (Mentioned as an option <a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=58s">Video
              0:58-1:00</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Observe weight-bearing posture, arches.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Gait:</strong> "tell the patient to take few steps... I
            will check the Gate of the patient" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=61s">Video
              1:01-1:09</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>Observe for limp, antalgia, abnormalities in heel strike,
                stance, toe-off.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Sitting/Supine:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Swelling, scars, sinuses, ulcers.</li>
              <li>Muscle wasting (intrinsic muscles of foot, calf).</li>
              <li>Nail changes.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. PALPATION (FEEL) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=74s">Video
            1:14</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(Keep looking at the patient's face for any kind of tenderness (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=100s">Video
              1:40</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=110s">Video
              1:50</a>). Compare both sides.)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> Check on both sides and compare. (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=76s">Video
              1:16-1:20</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Pulses:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Dorsalis Pedis. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=84s">Video
                  1:24-1:29</a>)</li>
              <li>Posterior Tibial. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=84s">Video
                  1:24-1:33</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Bony and Soft Tissue Tenderness:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Metatarsophalangeal (MTP) joints. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=96s">Video
                  1:36-1:44</a>)</li>
              <li>Tarsal bones. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=106s">Video
                  1:46-1:54</a>)</li>
              <li>Medial Malleolus. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=124s">Video
                  2:04-2:07</a>)</li>
              <li>Lateral Malleolus. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=127s">Video
                  2:07-2:13</a>)</li>
              <li>Calcaneum (patient's leg bent). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=135s">Video
                  2:15-2:24</a>)</li>
              <li>Achilles Tendon. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=146s">Video
                  2:26-2:30</a>)</li>
              <li>Anterior joint line.</li>
              <li>Sinus tarsi.</li>
              <li>Peroneal tendons.</li>
              <li>Plantar fascia.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. MOVEMENT (MOVE) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=159s">Video
            2:39</a>)</h4>
        <p><em>(Active movements demonstrated in video)</em></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ankle:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Plantarflexion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=161s">Video
                  2:41-2:44</a>)</li>
              <li>Dorsiflexion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=164s">Video
                  2:44-2:46</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Foot/Subtalar:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Inversion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=183s">Video
                  3:03-3:07</a>)</li>
              <li>Eversion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=187s">Video
                  3:07-3:13</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Toes:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Active Toe Flexion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=171s">Video
                  2:51-2:55</a>)</li>
              <li>Active Toe Extension. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=178s">Video
                  2:58-3:03</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>(Passive range of motion should also be assessed if active is
            limited or painful).</li>
          <li>(Midtarsal: Pronation/Supination - not explicitly shown but part
            of full exam).</li>
          <li>(1st MTP joint: Dorsiflexion/Plantarflexion - individual joint not
            specifically isolated in video beyond general toe movements).</li>
        </ul>
        <p><em>Video notes that a patient with an ankle sprain will have
            tenderness during palpation and limitation in movements (<a class="timestamp"
              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=198s">Video
              3:18-3:26</a>).</em></p>
        <h4>D. SPECIAL TESTS</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Anterior drawer test (ATFL integrity).</li>
          <li>Talar tilt test (CFL integrity).</li>
          <li>Thompson test (Achilles rupture) / Simmonds' test.</li>
          <li>Windlass test (plantar fasciitis).</li>
          <li>Morton's test (Morton's neuroma).</li>
          <li>(Coleman block test for pes cavus).</li>
          <li>(Squeeze test for syndesmosis injury).</li>
        </ul>
        <p><em><b>Completion of Examination:</b> "examine one joint above one
            joint below and make sure you do full neurological examinations" (<a
              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tjz24MT56A0&amp;t=209s">Video
              3:29-3:35</a>).</em></p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">EXPAND EXAMINATION: NEUROVASCULAR ASSESSMENT</summary>
        <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1kfg1mYRJ-g"
            title="Peripheral Vascular Examination - OSCE Guide (Latest) | UKMLA | CPSA | PLAB 2"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen=""
            height="704" frameborder="0" width="1237"></iframe> </div>
        <p class="ortho-specific"><em>(<b>Prerequisites:</b> Explain the
            procedure: "today I've been asked to perform a peripheral vascular
            exam..." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=17s">0:17</a>).
            Ensure adequate exposure. Obtain verbal consent: "...would that be
            okay?" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=24s">0:24</a>).
            Ensure patient is comfortable.)</em></p>
        <h4>CHAPERONE</h4>
        <h4>A. GENERAL INSPECTION (End of Bed)</h4>
        <ol>
          <li>Look for any objects or aids around the bed (e.g., mobility aids,
            medications).</li>
          <li>Assess the patient's general appearance (e.g., well/unwell,
            comfortable at rest).</li>
        </ol>
        <h4>B. UPPER LIMB ASSESSMENT</h4>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Inspection</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Ask the patient to hold their hands out. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=39s">0:39</a>)</li>
              <li> colour (pallor, cyanosis),</li>
              <li>tar staining, </li>
              <li>skin lesions, </li>
              <li>nail changes (splinter haemorrhages).</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Palpation</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>temperature of both hands and forearms, comparing sides. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=48s">0:48</a>)</li>
              <li>Assess Capillary Refill Time (CRT) on the fingertips (normal
                &lt;2 seconds).</li>
              <li>Palpate Pulses (assess rate, rhythm, and character):
                <ol>
                  <li>Radial Pulse. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=65s">1:05</a>)</li>
                  <li>Brachial Pulse. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=80s">1:20</a>)</li>
                </ol>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h4>C. CENTRAL &amp; LOWER LIMB VASCULAR ASSESSMENT</h4>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Carotid Arteries</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Auscultate for bruits first (ask patient to hold their
                breath). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=98s">1:38</a>)</li>
              <li>Palpate the carotid pulse (one side at a time). (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=114s">1:54</a>)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Abdominal Aorta</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Inspect the abdomen for visible pulsations. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=126s">2:06</a>)</li>
              <li>Palpate for an expansile mass. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=132s">2:12</a>)</li>
              <li>Auscultate for an aortic bruit. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=146s">2:26</a>)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Lower Limbs - Inspection</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>colour, </li>
              <li>hair loss, </li>
              <li>ulcers, </li>
              <li>scars, </li>
              <li>wasting.</li>
              <li>Ask patient to wiggle their toes to assess motor function. (<a
                  class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=193s">3:13</a>)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Lower Limbs - Palpation</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Assess temperature of both legs, comparing sides. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=199s">3:19</a>)</li>
              <li>Palpate Pulses:
                <ol>
                  <li>Femoral Pulse. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=224s">3:44</a>)</li>
                  <li>Check for Radio-Femoral Delay. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=243s">4:03</a>)</li>
                  <li>Popliteal Pulse. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=268s">4:28</a>)</li>
                  <li>Posterior Tibial Pulse.</li>
                  <li>Dorsalis Pedis Pulse.</li>
                </ol>
              </li>
              <li>circumference of the calf</li>
              <ol>
                <li>swollen</li>
                <li>wasted</li>
              </ol>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h4>D. SPECIAL TESTS</h4>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Buerger's Test</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Elevate the patient's legs to 45 degrees and hold for 1-2
                minutes. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=324s">5:24</a>)</li>
              <li>Observe for pallor (whiteness) of the feet.</li>
              <li>Ask the patient to sit up and hang their legs over the side of
                the bed. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=347s">5:47</a>)</li>
              <li>Observe for reactive hyperaemia (a deep, dusky red colour),
                indicating peripheral arterial disease.</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h4>E. NEUROLOGICAL ASSESSMENT (Distal)</h4>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sensation</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Test light touch in the dermatomes of the foot, comparing left
                and right. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=300s">5:00</a>)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Motor Function</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Assess power in movements like ankle dorsiflexion,
                plantarflexion, and toe extension. (Partially assessed by asking
                to wiggle toes).</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Reflexes</strong>
            <ol>
              <li>Check ankle (Achilles) reflex.</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h4>F. COMPLETION OF EXAMINATION</h4>
        <ol>
          <li>Thank and allow them to get dressed. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=356s">5:56</a>)</li>
          <li>Summarise findings. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=360s">6:00</a>)</li>
          <li>State further investigations to complete the assessment:
            <ol>
              <li>Measure blood pressure in both arms. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=379s">6:19</a>)</li>
              <li>Perform an Ankle-Brachial Pressure Index (ABPI). (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=381s">6:21</a>)</li>
              <li>Perform a full cardiovascular examination. (<a class="timestamp"
                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1kfg1mYRJ-g&amp;t=381s">6:21</a>)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <h4>G. WELL's SCORE</h4>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary class="h3">E. NEUROVASCULAR ASSESSMENT (Distal to affected
          area)</summary>
        <ul>
          <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1kfg1mYRJ-g"
              title="Peripheral Vascular Examination - OSCE Guide (Latest) | UKMLA | CPSA | PLAB 2"
              allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
              referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen=""
              height="704" frameborder="0" width="1237"></iframe> </div>
          <li><strong>Vascular:</strong> </li>
          <li><strong>Neurological:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Sensation: </li>
              <ul>
                <li>Light touch, </li>
                <li>pinprick in dermatomal for relevant nerves)</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Motor function: </li>
              <ul>
                <li>Test specific myotomes/muscles distal to the injury/affected
                  area, can be part of 'Move')</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Reflexes: </li>
              <ul>
                <li>(for concerned part e.g.,
                  <ul>
                    <li>biceps,</li>
                    <li>triceps,</li>
                    <li>brachioradialis,</li>
                    <li>patellar,</li>
                    <li>Achilles. Plantar response.)</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>MEASUREMENTS (if relevant):</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Limb length (true and apparent)</li>
          <li>Angular deformities</li>
        </ul>
      </details>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>X. SUMMARY OF FINDINGS</h3>
      <p>[A concise summary of the pertinent positive and negative findings from
        the history and physical examination. e.g., "Mr./Ms. X, a Y-year-old
        [occupation], presented with [chief complaint(s)] for [duration],
        following [mechanism of injury if any / insidious onset]. Key historical
        points include... Examination revealed [key findings like deformity,
        swelling, tenderness at..., restricted ROM in..., positive special tests
        like..., neurovascular status intact/compromised...]."]</p>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>XI. PROVISIONAL DIAGNOSIS</h3>
      <p>[Most likely diagnosis based on history and examination. Be specific
        about location and type of injury/condition.]</p>
      <p>e.g., 1. Acute Anterior Cruciate Ligament (ACL) tear, Right Knee.</p>
      <p>e.g., 2. Osteoarthritis of the Left Hip, severe.</p>
      <p>e.g., 3. Pathological fracture of the Right Femur, secondary to
        suspected metastasis.</p>
      <p>e.g., 4. Lumbar disc herniation L4/L5 with right L5 radiculopathy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>XII. DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSES</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>[Differential 1, with brief reasoning]</li>
        <li>[Differential 2, with brief reasoning]</li>
        <li>[Differential 3, with brief reasoning]</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>XIII. INVESTIGATIONS PLANNED</h3>
      <p class="ortho-specific">(Tailor to provisional diagnosis and
        differentials, guided by NICE principles for appropriateness and
        pathway.)</p>
      <h4>A. LABORATORY TESTS</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Baseline (if surgery considered or systemic illness
            suspected):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Full Blood Count (FBC), Differential Count (DC)</li>
            <li>Urea &amp; Electrolytes (U&amp;Es) / Renal Function Test (RFT)</li>
            <li>Liver Function Tests (LFTs)</li>
            <li>Clotting Screen (PT/INR, APTT) - if on anticoagulants or surgery
              planned</li>
            <li>Group and Save / Crossmatch - if significant blood loss
              anticipated</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Inflammatory Markers:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR)</li>
            <li>C-Reactive Protein (CRP) - (For infection, inflammatory
              arthritis)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Specific Tests:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Bone Profile: Calcium, Phosphate, Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP) -
              (Metabolic bone disease, tumors, fractures)</li>
            <li>Uric Acid - (Suspected Gout)</li>
            <li>Rheumatoid Factor (RF), Anti-Cyclic Citrullinated Peptide
              (Anti-CCP) antibodies - (Suspected RA)</li>
            <li>Antinuclear Antibody (ANA), Extractable Nuclear Antigens (ENA) -
              (Connective tissue diseases)</li>
            <li>HLA-B27 - (Suspected Spondyloarthropathy)</li>
            <li>Blood cultures - (Suspected septic arthritis, osteomyelitis)</li>
            <li>Serum Protein Electrophoresis (SPEP), Urine Bence Jones Protein
              - (Suspected Myeloma)</li>
            <li>Thyroid Function Tests (TFTs)</li>
            <li>Vitamin D levels</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Joint Aspiration / Synovial Fluid Analysis:</strong> (If
          effusion present and infection/crystal arthropathy suspected)
          <ul>
            <li>Appearance, WBC count and differential, Gram stain, Culture
              &amp; Sensitivity, Crystal microscopy (for urate, CPPD)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h4>B. IMAGING</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>X-rays:</strong> (Standard initial imaging for most
          orthopedic conditions)
          <ul>
            <li>Affected area: (AP, Lateral views minimum. Oblique, special
              views like skyline for patella, stress views for instability,
              weight-bearing views for OA assessment as appropriate)</li>
            <li>Comparison views of contralateral side (especially in
              pediatrics)</li>
            <li>Chest X-ray (pre-op, suspected mets)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Ultrasound (US):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Soft tissue injuries (tendon tears, bursitis, collections,
              synovitis)</li>
            <li>Guided aspirations or injections</li>
            <li>Assessment of infant hip (DDH screening)</li>
            <li>Foreign body localization</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Computed Tomography (CT) Scan:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Complex fractures (intra-articular, pelvic, spinal), fracture
              characterization, pre-operative planning</li>
            <li>Bone tumors (extent, cortical breach)</li>
            <li>Spinal stenosis, disc herniation (if MRI contraindicated or for
              bony detail)</li>
            <li>CT Angiography (vascular injury)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Soft tissue injuries (ligaments, tendons, menisci, cartilage)</li>
            <li>Spinal cord/nerve root compression (disc herniation, stenosis,
              tumors)</li>
            <li>Bone marrow pathology (stress fractures, AVN, osteomyelitis,
              tumors)</li>
            <li>Occult fractures not seen on X-ray</li>
            <li>Pre-operative planning for specific procedures</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Bone Scan (Radionuclide Scintigraphy):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Detection of occult fractures, stress fractures</li>
            <li>Metastatic bone disease screening</li>
            <li>Osteomyelitis, Paget's disease</li>
            <li>Loosening/infection of joint replacements</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>DEXA Scan (Dual-Energy X-ray Absorptiometry):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Assessment of bone mineral density (Osteoporosis diagnosis and
              monitoring)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h4>C. OTHER</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Nerve Conduction Studies (NCS) / Electromyography (EMG):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Peripheral nerve injuries, entrapment neuropathies (e.g., carpal
              tunnel syndrome), radiculopathy, myopathy</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Biopsy:</strong> (Bone or soft tissue - for suspected tumor
          or infection. Image-guided or open)</li>
        <li><strong>Compartment Pressure Measurement:</strong> (Suspected
          compartment syndrome)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h3>XIV. MANAGEMENT PLAN</h3>
      <p class="ortho-specific">(Based on diagnosis, patient factors, and NICE
        guidelines. Discuss conservative vs. surgical options.)</p>
      <h4>A. IMMEDIATE MANAGEMENT (If any, e.g., in ER for acute trauma)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>PRICE:</strong> Painkiller/Protection, Rest, Ice,
          Compression, Elevation (mnemonic)</li>
        <li><strong>Analgesia:</strong> (e.g., Paracetamol, NSAIDs, Opioids -
          follow NICE pain ladder)</li>
        <li><strong>Immobilization:</strong> (Sling, splint, cast, backslab -
          specify type)</li>
        <li><strong>Reduction of dislocation/fracture:</strong> (If applicable,
          document method and post-reduction status)</li>
        <li><strong>Neurovascular checks:</strong> (Document pre and
          post-intervention)</li>
        <li><strong>Tetanus prophylaxis:</strong> (If open fracture/wound)</li>
        <li><strong>Antibiotics:</strong> (If open fracture - e.g., Co-amoxiclav
          or Cefuroxime +/- Metronidazole, as per local guidelines/NICE)</li>
        <li><strong>Admission / Referral:</strong> (Criteria for urgent
          orthopedic review/admission e.g. open fracture, neurovascular
          compromise, irreducible dislocation, compartment syndrome, cauda
          equina, septic arthritis)</li>
      </ul>
      <h4>B. DEFINITIVE MANAGEMENT</h4>
      <p><strong>Patient Communication (ICE - Ideas, Concerns, Expectations):</strong>
        Discuss diagnosis, findings, treatment options, risks/benefits,
        prognosis.</p>
      <h5>1. CONSERVATIVE MANAGEMENT</h5>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Patient Education &amp; Advice:</strong> (Condition
          explanation, activity modification, self-management strategies, red
          flag signs)</li>
        <li><strong>Lifestyle Modification:</strong> (Weight management for
          OA/back pain, smoking cessation for fracture healing, ergonomic
          advice)</li>
        <li><strong>Analgesia (NICE Pain Ladder):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Step 1: Paracetamol +/- Topical NSAIDs (for OA).</li>
            <li>Step 2: Oral NSAIDs (consider PPI cover, lowest effective dose,
              shortest duration) or COX-2 inhibitors.</li>
            <li>Step 3: Opioids (weak e.g., codeine; or strong e.g., morphine,
              oxycodone for short-term severe pain or if other options
              contraindicated/ineffective. Caution with long-term use. Consider
              laxatives).</li>
            <li>Neuropathic agents (e.g., Amitriptyline, Gabapentin, Pregabalin
              for neuropathic pain - as per NICE CG173).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Physiotherapy / Occupational Therapy:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Exercise prescription (strengthening, stretching, range of
              motion, proprioception, core stability).</li>
            <li>Manual therapy.</li>
            <li>Gait re-education.</li>
            <li>Provision of aids (crutches, walkers, splints, orthotics).</li>
            <li>Home environment assessment and adaptation.</li>
            <li>Return to work/sport rehabilitation.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Injections (Image-guided where appropriate, as per NICE):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Corticosteroid injections (for joint inflammation, bursitis,
              tenosynovitis, trigger finger, nerve blocks. NICE has specific
              guidance on use e.g. for OA knee).</li>
            <li>Hyaluronic acid injections (Viscosupplementation - NICE guidance
              varies, often not routinely recommended for OA).</li>
            <li>Platelet-Rich Plasma (PRP) - (Use in specific conditions, often
              limited NICE endorsement).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Immobilization/Support:</strong> (Casts, braces, splints,
          collars - for fractures, instability, severe pain)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>2. SURGICAL MANAGEMENT</h5>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Indications for surgery:</strong> (Failure of conservative
          management, specific types of fractures, instability, severe
          deformity, neurological compromise, patient preference after informed
          consent. Refer to NICE guidelines for specific procedures e.g., joint
          replacement CG177, hip fracture CG124).</li>
        <li><strong>Pre-operative Assessment:</strong> (Medical fitness for
          surgery, optimization of co-morbidities, anaesthetic review).</li>
        <li><strong>Informed Consent:</strong> (Details of procedure, benefits,
          risks, alternatives, post-op recovery).</li>
        <li><strong>Type of Surgery Planned:</strong> (e.g., Open Reduction
          Internal Fixation (ORIF), Intramedullary Nailing, Joint Replacement
          (Total/Hemiarthroplasty), Arthroscopy (diagnostic/therapeutic - e.g.,
          meniscectomy, ligament reconstruction), Debridement, Osteotomy, Fusion
          (Arthrodesis), Amputation, Tendon repair, Nerve decompression).</li>
        <li><strong>Post-operative Care:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Pain management.</li>
            <li>Wound care.</li>
            <li>DVT prophylaxis (mechanical and/or pharmacological - as per NICE
              CG92).</li>
            <li>Antibiotic prophylaxis (as per NICE CG74).</li>
            <li>Mobilization plan / Rehabilitation protocol.</li>
            <li>Weight-bearing status.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h4>C. FOLLOW-UP PLAN</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Frequency and timing of follow-up appointments (e.g., outpatient
          clinic, fracture clinic).</li>
        <li>Monitoring of symptoms, function, and recovery.</li>
        <li>Radiological follow-up (if needed, e.g., fracture healing, implant
          position).</li>
        <li>Referrals to other specialists if needed (e.g., Rheumatology, Pain
          Management, Neurology).</li>
        <li>Long-term plan, including return to activities/work.</li>
      </ul>
      <h4>D. PATIENT EDUCATION (REINFORCE)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Warning Signs/Red Flags requiring urgent attention:</strong>
          (e.g., signs of infection - fever, redness, pus; DVT/PE - calf
          pain/swelling, SOB, chest pain; neurovascular compromise - numbness,
          weakness, color change; cast too tight).</li>
        <li><strong>Information on condition and management.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Expected recovery timeline.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Importance of adherence to physiotherapy/rehabilitation.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Contact information for concerns.</strong></li>
        <li><strong>Provision of leaflets/links to reliable resources (e.g.,
            NICE patient information, Versus Arthritis).</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <script src="harsha_iframe_youtube_player.js"></script>
    <script src="Iframe_height_mothership.js"></script>
    <script src="Iframe_height.js"></script>
    <script src="theme-toggle.js"></script>
    <script src="double_click_collapse_details.js"></script>
  </body>
